{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778709607,"nonce":"N+PTb7CHwA3hN5nbiCgCWz6wdkY=","message":"**Two related RunPod operational gaps surfaced in the b399efc deployment (2026-05-13)**:\n\n**1. Sequential-default for matrix runs is wrong.** The orchestrator's deployment brief biased the subagent toward running the 7-cell movement-ramp matrix sequentially, with parallel as an \"optional 2-at-a-time if VRAM allows.\" Result: each cell takes ~10-15 min, total ~1.5-2 hours wall-clock and $1.50-2 billed. Reality: each cell uses ~3.2 GB on the 5090 (32 GB total). All 7 cells fit comfortably in parallel under `XLA_PYTHON_CLIENT_PREALLOCATE=false` (demand-driven allocation). The parallel runtime ceiling is ~15-20 min wall-clock — a 5-7× speedup at no incremental cost. The default for a warmup-only matrix should be **all cells in parallel** unless an explicit VRAM constraint is documented. Sequential is the right choice only when (a) JIT compilation cache is shared meaningfully across cells, (b) VRAM doesn't fit the matrix, or (c) the runs are too long-lived for a single pod allocation. None of those applied here.\n\n**2. SSH connection flakiness blocks rapid mid-flight intervention.** During this session, SSH to the pod intermittently returned `exit 255` with no other error info, requiring 5-15s waits between retries. When the user discovered the sequential default mid-flight and asked to switch to parallel, killing the running serial orchestrator (`launch_matrix.sh`) and launching the remaining 6 cells in parallel required several SSH attempts with backoff. This is workable but adds friction precisely when intervention is most urgent (training is running, billing is accruing, and the longer the orchestrator runs sequential the more compute is wasted). Possible mitigations:\n  - Bake mid-flight intervention helpers into the deploy runbook (`§`-numbered procedures for \"kill orchestrator, keep current cell, parallelize rest\").\n  - Use `ServerAliveInterval=15 ConnectTimeout=60` SSH defaults rather than the runbook's bare `ssh -i ...` form.\n  - Possibly multiplex via `ControlMaster` so one persistent connection survives flakes.\n\nBoth observations from rlrmp tracking issue `b399efc` matrix deployment, 2026-05-13 evening.","files":null}]}